  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why don't most of the female artistic gymnasts develop hips?",
  "response": "Female artistic gymnasts often start training at a very young age, and the intense physical demands of the sport can influence their physical development in several ways. Here are some reasons why many female gymnasts may not develop pronounced hips:\n\n1. **Low Body Fat**: Gymnastics requires a high level of strength and flexibility, and maintaining a low body fat percentage is often necessary to perform at a competitive level. Since fat distribution around the hips and thighs contributes to the development of curves, having lower body fat can result in less pronounced hips.\n\n2. **Delayed Puberty**: The intense training and physical stress of gymnastics can delay the onset of puberty. Hormonal changes during puberty are responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics, including the widening of the hips. A delay in these hormonal changes can lead to a more linear body shape.\n\n3. **Bone Structure**: The type of physical activity involved in gymnastics, such as frequent jumping and weight-bearing exercises, can influence bone density and structure. The repetitive nature of these movements might affect how the pelvis and hips develop over time.\n\n4. **Genetics**: Genetic factors play a significant role in body shape and how an individual responds to training. Some gymnasts may naturally have a more slender build, which can be accentuated by their training regimen.\n\n5. **Muscle Development**: The specific muscle groups used in gymnastics tend to be the upper body and core, rather than the lower body. As a result, the muscles around the hips may not develop as much as in other athletes, contributing to a less curvy appearance.\n\nIt's important to note that these factors can vary widely among individual gymnasts, and not all will experience the same effects on their body development. Additionally, as gymnasts retire from the sport and their training intensity decreases, some may see changes in their body shape, including the development of more pronounced hips.",
